node.text: Zaki Anwari, a promising soccer player on Afghanistan’s national youth soccer team and high school student, was “among the hundreds of young people who wanted to leave the country” and died after falling from a US military plane, the national sports department said. It’s unclear exactly how old Anwari was. Media reports say he was 19 or 17. A bright student and a former member of the national under-16s team, Anwari wanted to be a world-class soccer player, his former teammate Rahil Abid told CBS News. “He dreamed of making Afghanistan a big name on the world stage,” Abid said. Earlier this week, crowds were seen running after a US Air Force plane on the runway with several people clinging to its side as it prepared to take off. Grisly videos circulating on social media show at least two people falling from the plane in the sky. To read more on this, tap the link in our bio. (📸: Facebook)

node.text: The family of Qismat Amin, a former interpreter for the US military, now face a threat confronted by thousands in Afghanistan who have helped the US government over the nearly 20 years it was in the country. The family has taken to hiding in their home, he said, leaving only to get food when necessary. Amin is particularly concerned about his brother, who also worked as an interpreter for more than a year. “We are trying to figure out how to have my family survive, to not be tortured or beheaded. I can’t focus. I’m not hungry. I can’t work,” he said. Read more through the link in our bio. (📸: Courtesy Qismat Amin; Josh Boak/The Washington Post via Getty Images)

node.text: Heavy rains from Tropical Storm Grace battered Haiti days after a deadly earthquake. Saturday’s magnitude-7.2 tremor killed more than 1,400 people and left tens of thousands of others without homes. Haiti is still reeling from the devastating 2010 earthquake that killed more than 200,000 people, as well as the assassination of its president last month and the ongoing coronavirus pandemic. Tap the link in bio to see more. node.text: As of August 15, at least 1,297 people were killed and thousands more injured after a 7.2 magnitude earthquake struck Haiti Saturday morning. The epicenter was about 125 kilometers, or 78 miles, west of Haiti’s capital of Port-au-Prince, according to the US Geological Survey. The disaster was the latest crisis to hit the Caribbean island nation, which is still reeling from the assassination of its president, the coronavirus pandemic, and a wave of gang violence. Additionally, the quake came just as the country’s vaccination campaign was getting underway. The US, the United Nations, and relief organizations have pledged to assist Haiti, which has never fully recovered from the catastrophic earthquake in 2010 that killed more than 200,000 people. Tap the link in our bio to read more. (📸: Anadolu Agency via Getty Images; Joseph Odelyn / AP; Stanley Louis / AFP via Getty Images; Ralph Tedy Erol / Reuters; Joseph Odelyn / AP)

node.text: In April, a herd of 15 elephants in China meandered more than 800 miles from the city of Pu’er to the city of Kunming in June, gaining legions of fans along the way. The herd, which officials said was finally reaching a protected habitat in southwest China’s Yunnan province, had been migrating in search of food and a home, though no one knew exactly where they were going. According to Reuters, state protection efforts have enabled the wild elephant population of the Chinese state of Xishuangbanna to double since 1978. A ban on hunting activities also made elephants more willing to enter human communities. More than 150,000 people were evacuated from homes in the elephants’ path, but the animals have become local darlings as fans track their progress. For World Elephant Day this Aug. 12, @buzzfeedphoto took a look at some of the highlights of their journey. Tap the link in our bio for more and follow @world for more news from around the globe🐘🌏 (📸: China Daily / Reuters; VCG via Getty Images)

The causes of the blazes have yet to be determined, although they are inextricably linked to human-caused climate change. Tap the link in bio to read more. node.text: Gianmarco Tamberi of Italy and Mutaz Essa Barshim of Qatar both flawlessly completed a jump of 2.37 meters (7 feet, 9 1/4 inches). They then both attempted a jump of 2.39 meters, but neither could make it after three attempts each. According to the rules, they could either settle it with a jump-off or share the gold. “Can we have two golds?” Barshim asked the official. Barshim and Tamberi are rivals, but they’re also friends who have been there for each other through international competitions and even injuries. “He is one of my best friends, not only on the track, but outside the track. We work together. This is a dream come true,” Barshim said after the win, @cbc reported. Tap the link in the bio to read more 🥇🥇 (📸: Picture Alliance / DPA / Picture Alliance via Getty Images; Ian Macnicol / Getty Images)

node.text: Tokyo hosted its first modern Olympics in 1964, and it looked very different from the summer games being held today. Click our link in bio to see more archival photos 🇯🇵(📸: Al Fenn / Getty Images, Bettmann / Bettmann Archive)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by BuzzFeed World on July 27, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Uzbekistan's Oksana Chusovitina Received A Standing Ovation At Her Eighth And Final Olympic Games OFB C @world YO 20'.

node.text: The 46-year-old, two-time Olympic medalist representing Uzbekistan, finished her historic Olympic career with a vault performance, which failed to qualify her for the finals. Her emotional parting elicited many tears and cheers — from spectators, fellow competitors, and even judges. “I think I am one of the pioneers to let every woman know that you can be a wife, you can be a daughter, you can be a mother, and you can be an Olympic athlete and an Olympic medalist. Anything is possible, and age is just a number,” she told Inside Gymnastics Magazine back in May. Chusovitina has attended the games since the 1992 Summer Olympics. She was inducted into the International Gymnastics Hall of Fame in May 2017 and was named the Best Athlete of Decade (2011-2020) in Uzbekistan by the public vote held by the National Olympic Committee of Uzbekistan, according to the Olympics website 🤸(📸: Kazuhiro Nogi/AFP via Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by BuzzFeed World on July 26, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Weightlifter Hidilyn Diaz Wins First-Ever Gold Medal For The Philippines K TOKYO20 2 @world'.

node.text: Diaz, an Airwoman Sargent for the Philippine Air Force, just won gold in the women's 55kg weightlifting competition, earning the first gold medal ever for the Philippines. She set the Olympic Record for Women's 55kg by hoisting a combined weight of 224kg over her head. "I want to say to the young generation in the Philippines, 'You can have this dream of gold too,'" Diaz said to AFP. Back in the 2016 Summer Games in Rio, she won the silver medal to make her the first medalist ever for the Philippines. Tap the link in bio to read more. (📸: Chris Graythen/Getty Images)
